		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		 <tr>
		   <td><font face="verdana" size="2">Howdy, I'd just like to submit my question amidst the sea of others:<P>

 First of all, I'd like to thank you, Milo, on taking time out of your
daily life and answering the questions of the gaming public without any sort of clear benefit.  Are we an outlet for your malicious energy and frustration towards the world, or are you just bored?<P>

 Anyway, thanks.  My question is, why were you the only modeler of your
type on the entire EverQuest team during its development?  Surely a game of
this scope would've employed at least that of a smaller game, considering the sheer amount of models needed.  Did the game have a low budget and that point or something?<P>

 I also wanted to get your opinion on the only other high-profile game that
I know of with a skeletal animation system: Half-Life.  I absolutely love
how well the models animate in the game, and yet they're extremely detailed.
My friend and I had quite a bit of fun in a deathmatch by just toying around with what the various models did after certain actions.  The models in EverQuest animate well, but because of its massively multiplayer architecture, it really can't be as fluid as an offline game.  What's your opinion on Half-Life?<P>

 Thanks for your time!<P>

 - Jake Whiton
<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>
   I don't know for sure why I was EQ's only character modeler, and I'd
rather not talk about this in public -- I like my job, and I don't need
someone's misapprehension of my speculations threatening my livelihood.
My first guess would be that budget restrictions disallowed more than
one character modeler, but that's one of several good possibilities.<P>

   Oh, I've never played Half-Life.  I've not even seen it.  Almost every
game that came out during EQ's production phase never made it onto
my PC or PlayStation.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 Hey there.<P>

 What's your take on:<BR>
 a) Laissez-faire capitalism;<BR>
 b) Communism;<BR>
 c) The ethical issues which accompany cloning;<BR>
 d) The 2nd law of thermodynamics;<BR>
 e) The recent studies out of MIT which claim that males have the ability to compute problems 40% faster than females;<BR>
 f) Plato's Republic.<P>

 Just wonderin', d00d. Since I like to hear the opinions of intelligent people on intelligent topics, and I find you intelligent, I thought I'd
 ask.<P>

