<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

 Hey, Milo.<P>

 First of all, I applaud your stance on the language issue, even though, of course, you had the prerequisite error that should be present in every language/spelling flame (I mean, 'one *in* the same'? Seriously.).<P>

 I find it somewhat frightening that of all the English-speaking people I have typed to on the 'Net, only a minority seems to have some grasp of grammar and spelling. Now, I'm not even holding myself up as some
linguistic paragon - I don't think I'm all that fantastic a writer, but the fact that
I am part of the aforementioned minority just makes it all that much more dismaying, considering that this is my _third_ language (being a Swede raised in Austria).<P>

 However, (and this isn't your area, but you may want to kick the message over to someone at Verant who _is_ responsible) your stance _is_ rather ironic coming from a developer on a game which contains such gems as "Time to die a spiderling", "Bring pride on our name Terax" and "Stand where you are scum", which suggest, in order; that 'die' is now a synonym for
'kill', that a vocational guild changes its name to the player character's after training, and that there is a specific area where one should stand in
order to be scum. All of this due to the omittance of the very simple, yet crucial, comma before a direct address - something I would assume that any moderately literate person would be aware of. This is consistent
throughout the game, and not just in the three examples listed.<P>

 Other linguistic errors abound, from the misspelling of 'beckon' without a 'k' in the Bards' corpse locating song and the continued use of 'aquaduct' for aqu_e_duct, to the fact that the NPCs seem unable to drop the definite article when addressing monsters and the double pluralisation of 'You receive 6 silver pieces for the Spider Legs(s)'. The first two are presumably just typos, although it's rather worrisome that in the time the game has been around it has not been caught or corrected. As for the last examples, is it really that hard to program the NPCs to drop the first two characters of any name starting with 'a ' and the first three of one with 'an '? Is it impossible to set 'singular' and 'plural' flags on items, so that the sentence adjusts accordingly when they are mentioned? I'm not a programmer by any stretch of the imagination, but from my outsider's standpoint, this seems to be _far_ easier than getting the spells to work right, sharpening the AI, placing and balancing Quests, making the 3D environment work, etc.<P>

 I'm genuinely curious why this issue, which seriously damages at least
_my_ immersion in the game world, hasn't been addressed. I hope that the answer lies more in the actual difficulty of doing it, than in some sort of complacency. Language is probably the most important tool we have, and to take the attitude that "it doesn't matter" is very short-sighted.<P>

 Hey, I still love the game, despite its flaws (and I could write an even longer one about the interface), and will continue to adventure in Norrath for a long time, I'm sure, but I do think a language patch might be in order.<P>

 Regards, etc.<P>

 John
<P> <P><b><i>
