<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 inside this empty skull of mine :<P>

 1) When you are about to start on a model, what do you begin with ? The largest part of the body ? Or perhaps the left foremost finger that have a spot on it ?<P>

 2) What is - in your opinion - most important part in modeling a figure
that will be animated versus one that will not be animated (ie. like a a human
 vs. a rock) ?<P>

 3) Do you have a way to keep yourself motivated in order to get up in the morning, even if you feel a bit burned out ?<P>

 4) If you absolutely have to buy junkfood, what do you prefer then ?
Pizza, barbeque, McDonald stuff or do you just go for a twinkie or two with
cofee, like most of the cops do ?<P>

 Anker Steadfast<BR>
 Barbarian Warrior<BR>
 Innoruuk Server<BR>
 *Account now cancelled - No more Internet at home :(

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   (1)  I almost always begin with the torso.  It tends to be the central
         section from which everything else emanates.<P>

   (2) As distinct from an object with no moving parts, the most salient
         part of modeling an animated character is taking into account
         how it will move, and building it accordingly.  In fact, the
ability
         to do this well is generally the kind of thing that separates the
         men from the boys, so to speak.<P>

   (3) I ran out of tricks a long time ago, but John Smedley, Verant's
        CEO, recently came up with something that has been *very*
        effective.<P>

   (4) Well, I never *have* to buy junkfood, but on those occasions
         when I eat it, I usually go for a good hamburger, because I love
         those (and I always shall).<P> <P>
